{
  "mitigation_currently_implemented": "Configure switch-port ingress policing and enable storm-control on the Cisco switch port where UbuntuComputer is connected to enforce a strict per-host packet rate (limit ICMP/unicast packets) and drop excess traffic at L2.",
  "comments": "I changed the switch configuration to use per-port storm-control with low packet-per-second (pps) thresholds on Gi0/1 — 10 pps (with a lower burst parameter) for unicast/multicast/broadcast — to mitigate small-packet ICMP floods more effectively than bps policing. This targets packet-rate floods (pps) rather than throughput (bps), which is appropriate for the observed hping3 attack of ~10 packets per second. I applied the commands and attempted verification commands; if the platform image doesn't support storm-control pps or the commands returned no output, try 'show running-config interface GigabitEthernet0/1' and 'show interface GigabitEthernet0/1' locally. After applying, you should verify counters for input drops and confirm that the flood packet rate is reduced by observing drops on the interface and lower outbound ICMP traffic seen on FortiGate/snort. If the device doesn't support pps storm-control, use the alternate approach in my previous message (ACL + class-map + policy-map policing with a calculated bps rate equivalent to a low pps). Do not shut down the port or disconnect the host — only drop excess packets. ",
  "device_identifier": "cisco-switch",
  "commands": [
    "configure terminal\ninterface GigabitEthernet0/1\n description UbuntuComputer-port\n storm-control unicast level pps 10 5\n storm-control multicast level pps 10 5\n storm-control broadcast level pps 10 5\n exit\nend\nwrite memory",
    "show running-config interface GigabitEthernet0/1",
    "show interface GigabitEthernet0/1 | include packets input|packets output|packets now|Last input|Last output|input queue drops|output queue drops|Total output drops"
  ]
}
